The following are the criteria that contributed to the composite score

The number of basic patents (patent families) filed by the organization. This is an indication of research output that has a potential for commercial value. The number is limited only to those patents that are registered with the World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO).
The ratio of patent applications to grants over the assessed timeframe. This indicates the university?s success in filing applications that are then accepted.
The percentage of patents for which coverage was sought with the U.S.

Source: Web of Science Core Collection
Article-to-article citations are an established indicator of influence and research impact. By limiting the citing articles only to those from industry

The percentage of all articles of a university that contain one or more co-authors from a commercial entity. This indicator shows the percentage of research activity that is conducted in collaboration with industry
Total Web of Science Core Collection Papers
The total number of journal articles published by the organization. This is a size-dependent measure of the research output of the university.

The indicators were used to rank each of the universities and the composite score was achieved by summing the ranks for each criterion for each university. Each indicator was weighted equally with the exception of Patent Citation Impact and Percent of Patents Cited
